desc: Based on its small‐town predominantly rural character in Lubliniecki County (Śląskie) and comparing to other Polish countryside locations (many of which fell into the “Very Low” or “Low” bands) but noting Silesia’s somewhat stronger educational profile than say eastern voivodeships Koszęcin most plausibly falls into the “Low” class.

Based on its small‐village character in a largely rural part of the Gliwice area (without the strong suburban/commuter profile seen around Warsaw or Prague) Ligota Łabędzka’s share of university-educated residents would be expected to fall below the national rural average but above the most remote least-educated districts. In line with our five‐class benchmarks the most appropriate label is  
Low.

Based on its setting—a small village in Gmina Łazy Zawierciański (a largely rural part of Śląskie outside the main Katowice-Tychy conurbation)—we’d expect a below-average share of university graduates.  In the provided five-class scheme Rokitno Szlacheckie falls into the “Low” category.

Based on the location’s industrial-mining context in a small Silesian town (Rydułtowy Górne in Wodzisławski) which tends to have below-average tertiary‐education rates compared to major urban or academic centers the best qualitative match is: Low.

Based on its rural character—even if it lies within commuting distance of Toruń—and by analogy with other Polish villages outside major metro-area belts Toporzysko’s share of university‐educated residents would best be classified as Low.

Based on the typically low share of university‐educated residents in small rural villages of Podlaskie – even those in the orbit of Białystok – I’d classify Studzianki (gmina Wasilków powiat białostocki) as Low.

Based on its proximity to Szczecin (a major university city) the presence of a mid‐sized county town (Goleniów) and commuting links—but without the ultra-high educational pull of a capital agglomeration—I assess Goleniowski (Zachodniopomorskie) at the “Medium” level.
Based on its rural setting in the Koszalin area of West Pomerania and comparing to similar village‐level benchmarks the share of university‐educated residents in 76-009 Bonin is best classed as Low.

Based on the socio‐economic profile of Lubiński district (an industrial/mining area with a medium‐sized urban centre but no major university hub) its share of university graduates is likely around the regional average.  I would therefore classify Rynarcice (Powiat Lubiński) as: Medium.
Based on its location in an urban district of Łódź (home to a major university but with overall city‐wide tertiary attainment still below Warsaw’s) I’d classify Stary Widzew as Medium.

Przymorze Małe is an urban neighbourhood in Gdańsk – one of Poland’s three principal cities – with a dense concentration of students young professionals and higher-paid service-sector workers. While it doesn’t reach the absolute top tier you’d expect in a capital’s most elite quarters (Very High) its share of university-educated residents is well above the national average and even above that of many suburban locales. 

Answer: High

Based on its rural character (a small village in the Słupsk hinterland) and relatively limited local access to higher‐education institutions (despite being within commuting distance of Słupsk) the share of university graduates in Ochodza is likely below the national average but not at the very bottom. 
Answer: Low

Based on its status as a small rural village in the Gorzów area of Lubuskie—an otherwise lower‐educated province—and by analogy with similar Polish villages (most of which fall into the “Low” bracket) the share of university graduates in Bolemin is best classified as:

Answer: Low

Based on its location—a small village in the Płock County (a mid‐sized city rather than a major metro hub) within the generally high‐attainment Mazowieckie Voivodeship but still rural—you’d expect its share of university‐educated residents to sit in the middle of our regional benchmarks.  

Answer: Medium

Based on its proximity to the regional center Rzeszów (with its universities) yet still sitting in a predominantly rural province with below‐average tertiary attainment Świlcza in Rzeszowski County most closely aligns with a Medium level of highly educated residents.

Based on Mościce being an urban district of Tarnów (a city of ~110 000 in Małopolskie) with an industrial‐working-class character but still urban amenities and local higher-education institutions its share of university graduates is best classed as Medium.

Based on its status as a small village in the Małopolskie region (outside major urban centers but within commuting distance of Kraków) we’d expect a modest yet not extremely low share of university‐educated residents.  Compared against our qualitative benchmarks Kwaczała most plausibly falls into the “Medium” category.  Answer: Medium

Based on Slovakia’s regional tertiary‐education statistics (Prešov being one of the lowest‐ranked regions nationally) and the benchmarks from neighboring countries Prešov Kraj would fall into the “Low” class.

Based on the generally below‐national‐average tertiary attainment in the Karlovarský region (and in smaller spa towns like Loket) we would place its share of university‐educated residents in the “Low” category.

Based on regional education‐attainment statistics (Ústecký kraj’s tertiary‐education share sits well below the Czech average but above the most under-educated areas) I’d classify 418 04 Lukov Ústecký as: Low.

Based on its location in the moderately educated Pardubice Region and the fact that Bučina is a small rural settlement (so its university‐educated share will sit below the regional average of ~14 %) it falls into the “Low” category.

Based on its location in the Vysočina Region (a predominantly rural‐small-town area with only one mid-sized regional centre Jihlava and no major universities beyond a regional polytechnic college) Velký Beranov’s share of university graduates is likely around the national/regional average rather than at either extreme.  Therefore the most appropriate class is:

Medium

Based on its location in a rural part of Olomoucký kraj (with no immediate proximity to a major city centre like Olomouc itself) the share of tertiary‐educated residents is likely below the national/regional average but above the very lowest tier seen in the most remote villages. I would therefore classify Újezd (783 96) in Olomoucký kraj as: Low.

Answer: Very Low  
Söjtör is a small rural village in Zala County—a region whose higher‐education attainment rates lie well below the national Hungarian average. Similar rural settlements in Hungary (e.g. Nógrádsipek Zalaegerszeg környéke) fall into the “Very Low” category for share of university graduates. Given its demographic and economic profile Söjtör’s proportion of highly educated residents would likewise be classified as Very Low.

Based on Tiszakécske’s small-town setting in rural Bács-Kiskun—with no major universities and historically below-average tertiary attainment—the proportion of university graduates is best classified as: Low.
Based on Soltvadkert’s profile—a small town in the largely rural Bács-Kiskun county with below-national-average tertiary attainment—the share of university graduates is best classified as Low.
